Yes, this is possible in any protocol

For any kind of encryption you need to verify your contact's keys if you are concerned they may not be legitimate

No, this is a fundamental principle of all encryption

If you verify your contact's keys (using some appropriate mechanism) then MITM can't happen. If you don't verify them, it could.

the points *where* the MITM has to happen differ, of course.

for peer-to-peer things, the MITM generally _has_ to happen on the network paths between the peers, while for server-based things, the MITM may also happen by breaching the server.

